<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The world prices of iron ore and steel are strongly influenced by domestic and international supply and demand and global market conditions, all of which are uncertain.&#160; In addition, according to Cliffs&#146; most recent Form&nbsp;10-K for Cliffs&#146; fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015,
</FONT>
	filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission on February&nbsp;24, 2016, the current level of international demand for raw materials used in steel production is driven largely by industrial growth in China, which has been slowing significantly. Cliffs cautioned in its most recent Form&nbsp;10-K that continued weaknesses in global economic conditions, including the slowing economic growth rate in China, has resulted, and could in the future result, in decreased demand for its products and, together with oversupply of imported products, has and may continue to lead to decreased prices, resulting in lower revenue levels and decreasing margins, which have in the past and may in the future affect adversely its business and negatively impact its financial results. We are not able to predict how the global economic conditions, including the current slower growth and challenging economic conditions of China, will change or not change and the impact it may have on Cliffs&#146; and Northshore&#146;s operations and the iron ore and steel industries in general going forward. Cliffs also disclosed that (i)&nbsp;due to lower demand for our products and the decline in the prices for our products, it has incurred, and continues to incur, operating losses, (ii)&nbsp;it also has significant capital requirements, including interest payments to service its debt. If Cliffs incurs significant losses in future periods, and (iii)&nbsp;Cliffs believes that it may be unable to continue as a going concern. Cliffs also reported in its most recent Form&nbsp;10-K that if it is unable to continue as a going concern, it may consider, among other options, restructuring it debt although there can be no assurance that these options will be undertaken and, if so undertaken, whether these efforts will succeed.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Currently, there is a high degree of uncertainty concerning the overall demand for steel and iron ore products.&#160; Reduced demand for iron ore, especially due to a deceleration of economic growth in China, would likely result in decreased sales of products to Cliffs&#146; customers and decreasing prices, all of which would adversely affect royalties payable to the Trust.&#160; Since the Trust is not party to any specific customer contracts that Cliffs has with its customers and because these macroeconomic conditions are difficult to forecast, the Trustees are not able to predict the extent to which reduced demand and lower prices for iron ore products, if such circumstances continue, will adversely affect royalties payable to the Trust.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Although Cliffs reported that it has contractual commitments for a majority of sales in our U.S. Iron Ore business for 2016, it cautioned that the uncertainty in global economic conditions may adversely impact the ability of its customers to meet their obligations.&#160; As a result of such market volatility, Cliffs&#146; customers could approach Cliffs about modifying their supply agreements with Cliffs or fail to perform under such agreements. Considering Cliffs&#146; limited base of current and potential customers, any modifications to Cliffs&#146; sales agreements or customers&#146; failures to perform under such agreements could impact adversely Cliffs&#146; sales, margins, profitability and cash flows.
</FONT>
	Any modifications to such supply agreements, including reductions in pricing, or Cliffs&#146; customers&#146; failures to perform under such agreements could materially adversely affect the royalties payable to the Trust and, in turn, the cash available for distribution to Unitholders.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Cliffs has disclosed certain financial risks in its most recent annual report on Form&nbsp;10-K, including risks related to its substantial level of indebtedness, risks related to potential limitations on its ability to invest in the ongoing needs of its business, risks concerning its ability to generate sufficient cash flow to service all of its debt, and risks related to adverse changes in credit ratings, which may adversely affect its cost of financing
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Cliffs has disclosed in its most recent annual report on Form&nbsp;10-K filed on February&nbsp;24, 2016 that (i)&nbsp;due to its substantial level of indebtedness, it has to dedicate a substantial portion of its cash flow from operations to the payment of debt service, reducing the availability of its cash flow to fund working capital, capital expenditures, acquisitions and other general corporate purposes, (ii)&nbsp;if its cash flows and capital resources are insufficient to fund its debt service obligations, it may be forced to reduce or delay investments and capital expenditures, or to sell assets, seek additional capital or restructure or refinance its debt, including senior notes, which could be at higher interest rates and may require it to comply with more onerous covenants, which could further restrict its business operations, and (iii)&nbsp;credit rating agencies could further downgrade its ratings either due to factors specific to its business, a prolonged cyclical downturn in the mining industry, or macroeconomic trends (such as global or regional recessions) and trends in credit and capital markets more generally, which would likely result in an increase to its cost of financing, limit its access to the capital markets, significantly harm its financial condition and results of operations, and hinder its ability to refinance existing indebtedness on acceptable terms.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	These potential circumstances, if they become real developments, could have a material adverse effect on Cliffs and Northshore, which in turn, could have a material adverse effect on royalties paid to Mesabi Trust in the future.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Equipment failures and other unexpected events at Northshore may lead to production curtailments or shutdowns.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Interruptions in production capabilities at the mine operated by Northshore may have an adverse impact on the royalties payable to the Trust. In addition to planned production shutdowns or curtailments and equipment failures, the Northshore facilities are also subject to the risk of loss due to unanticipated events such as fires, explosions or extreme weather conditions. The manufacturing
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	5
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_5_121128_3020">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='5',FILE='C:\JMS\108184\16-4593-1\TASK7891368\4593-1-KU-01.HTM',USER='108184',CD='APR 15 00:46 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage20"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	processes that take place in Northshore&#146;s mining operations, as well as in Northshore&#146;s crushing, concentrating and pelletizing facilities, depend on critical pieces of equipment, such as drilling and blasting equipment, crushers, grinding mills, pebble mills, thickeners, separators, filters, mixers, furnaces, kilns and rolling equipment, as well as electrical equipment, such as transformers. It is possible that this equipment may, on occasion, be out of service because of unanticipated failures or unforeseeable acts of vandalism or terrorism.&#160; In addition, because the Northshore processing facilities have been in operation for several decades, some of the equipment is aged.&#160; Because the Trustees have no control over the operations or maintenance of the equipment at Northshore, a shutdown or reduction in capacity may come with little or no advance warning.&#160; The remediation of any interruption in production capability at Northshore could require Cliffs to make large capital expenditures which may take place over an extended period of time.&#160; Cliffs also stated in its most recent annual report that if its cash flows and capital resources are insufficient to fund its debt service obligations, it may be forced to reduce or delay investments and capital expenditures. At the end of November&nbsp;2015, Northshore shut down all of its taconite production lines. Cliffs reconfirmed in its most recent annual report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 filed on February&nbsp;24, 2016 that its Northshore operations are expected to be idled through at least the first quarter of 2016. Any additional idling, shutdown, reduction in operations, or production curtailment at Northshore would likely adversely affect the royalties payable to the Trust.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	The mining operations of Northshore are subject to extensive governmental regulations and Northshore is subject to risks related to its compliance with federal and state environmental regulations.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Northshore, as the operator of the mine on Mesabi Trust Lands, is subject to various federal, state and local laws and regulations on matters such as employee health and safety, air quality, water pollution, plant and wildlife protection, reclamation and restoration of mining properties, the discharge of materials into the environment, and the effects that mining has on groundwater quality and availability.&#160; Northshore is required to maintain permits and approvals issued by federal and state regulatory agencies and its mining operations are subject to inspection and regulation by the Mine Safety and Health Administration of the United States Department of Labor (&#147;MSHA&#148;) under the provisions of the Mine Safety and Health Act of 1977.&#160; The Occupational Safety and Health Administration (&#147;OSHA&#148;) has jurisdiction over safety and health standards not covered by MSHA and the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency (&#147;MPCA&#148;) regulates various aspects of Northshore&#146;s operations.&#160; Northshore may from time to time be involved in litigation with the MPCA over certain aspects of its operation but because the Trust has no control over Northshore&#146;s operations, the potential impact of these proceedings cannot be determined.&#160; Moreover, Northshore is solely responsible for its compliance with any laws, regulations or permits applicable to Northshore&#146;s operations and Northshore may at times fail to operate in compliance with such laws, regulations and permits.&#160; The Trust has no ability to control or determine whether Northshore has been or will in the future operate in compliance with such laws and regulations.&#160; If Northshore fails to comply with these laws, regulations or permits, it could be subject to fines or other sanctions, any of which could have an adverse effect on its operations and its ability to ship iron ore products from Silver Bay, Minnesota, which could, in turn, have a material adverse effect on the royalties paid to the Trust.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	TMDL (a regulatory term describing a value of the maximum amount of a pollutant that a body of water can receive while still meeting water quality standards under the Clean Water Act) regulations are contained in the Clean Water Act and as a part of Minnesota&#146;s Mercury TMDL Implementation Plan, in cooperation with the MPCA, the taconite industry developed a Taconite Mercury Reduction Strategy and signed a voluntary agreement to effectuate its terms. The strategy includes a 75 percent target reduction of mercury air emissions from Minnesota pellet plants collectively by 2025. For Cliffs, the requirements in the voluntary agreement do not apply to Northshore. Late in 2013, however, Minnesota published a draft mercury control rule&nbsp;that would require annual mercury emissions reporting and could require installation of mercury emission control equipment on all Cliffs&#146; Minnesota facilities including those of Northshore. On September&nbsp;22, 2014, Minnesota promulgated the Mercury Air Emissions Reporting and Reduction Rule&nbsp;mandating mercury air emissions reporting and reduction. The adopted rule&nbsp;expanded applicability to all of Cliffs&#146; Minnesota operations and requires submitting a mercury reduction plan in 2018 to reduce mercury emissions from all of Cliffs&#146; Minnesota taconite furnaces by 72 percent by January&nbsp;2025 and 70 percent reduction from Northshore&#146;s industrial boilers by January&nbsp;1, 2018. The adopted rule&nbsp;does not include all four Adaptive Management Criteria for evaluating mercury reduction, which were agreed upon in the October&nbsp;2009 Minnesota&#146;s Mercury TMDL Implementation Plan. According to Cliffs&#146; Form&nbsp;10-K filed February&nbsp;24, 2016, there is currently no proven technology to cost-effectively reduce mercury emissions from taconite furnaces to the target level of 72 percent that would meet all four Adaptive Management Criteria. Cliffs expressed its concerns about the technical and economic feasibility to reduce taconite mercury emissions by 72 percent and are conducting detailed engineering analysis to determine the impact of the regulations on each unique iron ore indurating furnace affected by this rule. The Trustees are unable to predict what impact, if any, the Mercury Air Emissions Reporting and Reduction Rule&nbsp;will have on production and shipments from Northshore or future royalties payable to the Trust.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In its Form&nbsp;10-K filed on February&nbsp;24, 2016, Cliffs also reported that on July&nbsp;6, 2011, the US Environmental Protection Agency (the &#147;EPA&#148;) promulgated the Cross State Air Pollution Rule&nbsp;(the &#147;CSAPR&#148;), which was intended to be an emissions trading rule&nbsp;for SO2 and NOx. Northshore&#146;s Silver Bay Power Plant would have been subject to this rule. CSAPR was vacated by the D.C. Circuit Court during the third quarter of 2012. Late in 2014, the Supreme Court re-instated CSAPR with an effective date of January&nbsp;1, 2015, reinstating the obligations of this rule&nbsp;for Silver Bay Power. Immediate compliance obligations are being met at this
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	6
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_6_121149_7748">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='6',FILE='C:\JMS\108184\16-4593-1\TASK7891368\4593-1-KU-01.HTM',USER='108184',CD='APR 15 00:46 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage21"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	time, with the material obligation being procurement of the first year of emissions allowances by March&nbsp;2016 for the 2015 operating year. Silver Bay Power is completing the engineering and permitting work to install controls that will limit the cost exposure to the trading market. The allowance pricing market indicates the annual costs to comply with CSAPR will be less than $0.2 million for 2015 and future allowance prices are anticipated to remain favorable under the existing framework. Cliffs also disclosed that it cannot reasonably estimate the long term impact of CSAPR should EPA reduce the allocations in response to future lower ozone or PM2.5 regulations. The Trustees are unable to predict what impact, if any, the emission reduction project will have on production and shipments from Northshore or future royalties payable to the Trust.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	The Trust does not control the portion of Northshore&#146;s shipments that will come from ore mined from Mesabi Trust Lands.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Trustees do not exert any influence over mining operational decisions at Northshore and Northshore alone determines whether to mine from Mesabi Trust Lands or state-owned lands, based on its current production estimates and engineering plan.&#160; Northshore&#146;s mining operations include Mesabi Trust Lands and mineral-producing land owned by the State of Minnesota and others.&#160; Ore mined by Northshore from lands other than Mesabi Trust Lands is processed, along with ore mined from Mesabi Trust Lands, in Northshore-owned crushing, concentrating and pelletizing facilities and is separately accounted for on a periodic basis.&#160; Northshore also has the ability to process and ship iron ore products from lands other than Mesabi Trust Lands.&#160; In certain circumstances, the Trust may be entitled to royalties on those other shipments, but not in all cases.&#160; In general, the Trust will receive higher royalties (assuming all other factors are equal) if a higher percentage of shipments is from Mesabi Trust Lands.&#160; The percentages of shipments from Mesabi Trust Lands were 88.9%, 90.8%, 93.5%, 93.9% and 88.5% in calendar years 2015, 2014, 2013, 2012, and 2011, respectively.&#160; If Northshore decides to materially reduce the percentage of ore mined, or pellets shipped, from Mesabi Trust Lands, the income of the Trust could be materially adversely affected.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Royalties payable to the Trust could be materially adversely affected by the failure of the Trust&#146;s independent consultants to competently perform.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As permitted by the terms of the Agreement of Trust and the Amendment, the Trustees are authorized to, and in fact do, rely upon certain independent consultants to assist the Trustees in carrying out and fulfilling their obligations as Trustees.&#160; Independent consultants perform services, render advice and produce reports with respect to monthly production and shipments, which include figures on crude ore production, iron ore pellet production, iron ore pellet shipments, and discussions concerning the condition and accuracy of the scales used to weigh iron ore pellets produced at Northshore&#146;s facilities.&#160; The Trustees have also retained an accounting firm to provide non-audit services, including preparing financial statements, reviewing financial data related to shipping and sales reports provided by Northshore and reviewing the schedule of leasehold and fee royalties payable to the Trust.&#160; The Trustees believe that the independent consultants are qualified to perform the services and functions assigned to them.&#160;&#160; Nevertheless, any negligence or the failure of any such independent consultants to competently perform could materially adversely affect the royalties to be received by the Trust.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	The Trust relies on Cliffs&#146; estimates of recoverable reserves, and if those estimates are inaccurate, the total potential future royalty stream to the Trust and distributions payable to Unitholders may be materially adversely affected.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Trustees do not participate in preparing the recoverable ore reserve estimates reported by Cliffs.&#160; According to Cliffs&#146; most recent Form&nbsp;10-K, Cliffs regularly evaluates its iron ore reserves based on revenues and costs and updates them as required in accordance with Securities Act Industry Guide&nbsp;7, promulgated by the Securities and Exchange Commission.&#160; In 2013, the Trustees engaged an independent firm of geological experts to evaluate the process Cliffs uses to estimate the recoverable iron ore reserves at the Peter Mitchell Mine.&#160; Still, there are numerous uncertainties inherent in estimating quantities of reserves of mineral producing lands and such estimates necessarily depend upon a number of variable factors and assumptions, such as production capacity, effects of regulations by governmental agencies, future prices for iron ore, future industry conditions and operating costs, severance and excise taxes, development costs and costs of extraction and reclamation costs, all of which may in fact vary considerably from actual results.&#160; All of these factors are outside of the control and influence of the Trustees.&#160; For these reasons, estimates of the economically recoverable quantities of mineralized deposits attributable to Mesabi Trust Lands and the classifications of such reserves based on the risk of recovery prepared by different engineers or by the same engineers at different times may vary substantially as the criteria change.&#160; Cliffs&#146; estimate of the ore reserves could be negatively affected by future industry conditions, geological conditions and ongoing mine planning at the Peter Mitchell Mine.&#160; Actual reserves will likely vary from estimates, and if such variances are negative and material, the expected royalties payable to the Trust could be materially adversely affected and the value of the Trust&#146;s Units could decline.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<A NAME="eolPage22"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">

	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Cliffs has disclosed certain operational risks, including risks that could arise related to substantial costs from announced and potential mine closures and risks related to its ability to transport its products to customers at competitive rates and in a timely manner.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Cliffs has disclosed in its most recent annual report on Form&nbsp;10-K filed on February&nbsp;24, 2016, that mine closures entail substantial costs, that it has idled its Wabush Scully mine in Newfoundland and Labrador, and in November&nbsp;2014 it began to implement the permanent closure plan for that mine. Cliffs also announced that its Canadian affiliates commenced restructuring proceedings under the Companies&#146; Creditors Arrangement Act (Canada) to mitigate closure costs in connection with the shutdown of the Bloom Lake mine. Effective January&nbsp;27, 2015, following the CCAA filing of the Bloom Lake Group, Cliffs deconsolidated the Bloom Lake Group and certain other wholly-owned subsidiaries comprising substantially all of its Canadian operations. Additionally, on May&nbsp;20, 2015, the Wabush Group commenced restructuring proceedings in Montreal, Quebec under the CCAA which resulted in the deconsolidation of the remaining Wabush Group entities that were not previously deconsolidated. Cliffs also disclosed that if it closes one or more of its own mines, Cliffs&#146; results of operations and financial condition would likely be affected adversely
<I>
	.
</I>
	Cliffs reconfirmed in its most recent annual report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 filed on February&nbsp;24, 2016 that its Northshore operations are expected to be idled through at least the first quarter of 2016. Any additional idling, shutdown, reduction in operations, or production curtailment at Northshore could adversely affect the royalties payable to the Trust.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Cliffs also disclosed that in its U.S. Iron Ore operations, disruption of the lake and ocean-going vessels and rail transportation services due to weather-related problems and lack of alternative transportation sources could impair Cliffs&#146; ability to supply iron ore to its customers at competitive rates or in a timely manner, and thus, could adversely affect its sales, margins and profitability. These events could have a material adverse effect on Cliffs and potentially Northshore, which in turn, could have a material adverse effect on royalties paid to Mesabi Trust in the future.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	The operations at Northshore are largely dependent on a single-source energy supplier.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The operations at Northshore are largely dependent on Silver Bay Power Company, a 115 megawatt power plant, for its electrical supply.&#160; Silver Bay Power Company, which is wholly owned by Northshore, has an interconnection agreement with Minnesota Power,&nbsp;Inc. for backup power when excess generation is necessary.&#160; A significant interruption in service from Silver Bay Power Company due to vandalism, terrorism, weather conditions, natural disasters, or any other cause could cause a decrease in production capacity or require a temporary shutdown of Northshore&#146;s operations.&#160; In addition, one natural gas pipeline serves all of Cliffs&#146; Minnesota mines, and a pipeline failure could idle or substantially impair the operations at Northshore.&#160; Any substantial interruption of, or material reduction in, Northshore&#146;s operations could materially adversely affect the royalties payable to the Trust.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	If steelmakers use methods other than blast furnace production to produce steel, or shut down or reduce production using blast furnaces, the demand for iron ore pellets may decrease.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In its annual report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the prior year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, filed February&nbsp;24, 2016, Cliffs reported that the d
</FONT>
	emand for Cliffs&#146; iron ore products is determined by the operating rates for the blast furnaces of steel companies although not all finished steel is produced by blast furnaces.&#160; Finished steel also may be produced by other methods that do not require iron ore pellets and use scrap steel, pig iron, hot briquetted iron and direct reduced iron. North American steel producers can also produce steel using imported iron ore or semi-finished steel products, which eliminates the need for domestic iron ore. Future environmental restrictions on the use of blast furnaces also may reduce the use of blast furnaces in steel production.&#160; Because the maintenance of blast furnaces can require substantial capital expenditures, steel manufacturers may choose not to maintain their blast furnaces, and some of them may not have the resources necessary to adequately maintain their blast furnaces. If steel manufacturers significantly alter the methods they use to produce steel or otherwise substantially reduce their use of iron ore pellets, demand for iron ore pellets will decrease, which could materially adversely affect the royalties payable to the Trust.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Certain risk factors affecting Cliffs&#146; North American Iron Ore Business generally, and Northshore operations in particular, could have a material adverse effect on the royalties payable to the Trust.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Because substantially all of the Trust&#146;s revenue is derived from iron ore products shipped by Northshore from Silver Bay, Northshore&#146;s iron ore pellet processing and shipping activities directly impact the Trust&#146;s revenues in each quarter and each year.&#160; A number of the risk factors, as disclosed by Cliffs in its most recent annual report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, affect Cliffs&#146; operations, and could impact Northshore&#146;s production and shipment volume.&#160; In its most recent Form&nbsp;10-K, Cliffs identified the following six categories of risk that Cliffs is subject to: (i)&nbsp;economic and market, (ii)&nbsp;regulatory, (iii)&nbsp;financial, (iv)&nbsp;operational, (v)&nbsp;development and sustainability, and (vi)&nbsp;human capital. These risk factors include, among others, the global economic climate and financial market conditions, economic conditions in the iron ore industry, extensive governmental regulations relating to environmental matters and the costs and risks related thereto, availability of substitute materials, pricing by domestic and international competitors, long-term customer contracts or arrangements by Northshore or its competitors, price adjustment provisions in Cliffs&#146; North American term supply agreements (which take into account various price indexes), availability of ore boats, production at Northshore&#146;s mining operations, natural disasters, shipping conditions in the Great Lakes and production at Northshore&#146;s pelletizing/processing facility.&#160; Specifically, if any portion of Northshore&#146;s pelletizing lines becomes idle for any reason, production, shipments and, consequently, the royalties payable to the Trust could be materially adversely affected.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	8
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_8_121254_7608">
</A>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='8',FILE='C:\JMS\108184\16-4593-1\TASK7891368\4593-1-KU-01.HTM',USER='108184',CD='APR 15 00:46 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage23"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	The Trustees are not subject to annual election and, as a result, the ability of the holders of Trust Certificates to influence the policies of the Trust may be limited.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Directors of a corporation are generally subject to election at each annual meeting of shareholders or, in the case of staggered boards, at regular intervals. Under the Agreement of Trust, however, the Trust is not required to hold annual meetings of holders of Trust Certificates to elect Trustees and Trustees generally hold office until their death, resignation or disqualification. As a result, the ability of holders of Trust Certificates to effect changes in the composition of the Board of Trustees and the policies of the Trust is significantly more limited than that of the shareholders of a corporation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	We are subject to the continued listing criteria of the NYSE, and our failure to satisfy these criteria may result in delisting of our units.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Our units are currently listed on the NYSE. In order to maintain the listing, we must maintain certain objective standards such as unit prices and a minimum number of public unitholders. In addition to objective standards, the NYSE may delist the securities of any issuer using subjective standards such as, if in the NYSE&#146;s opinion, the issuer&#146;s financial condition and/or operating results appear unsatisfactory or if any event occurs or any condition exists which makes continued listing on the NYSE inadvisable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	If the NYSE delists our units, unitholders may face material adverse consequences, including, but not limited to, a lack of trading market for our units, reduced liquidity, and decreased analyst coverage of our units.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	OVERVIEW OF TRUST&#146;S ROYALTY STRUCTURE
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Leasehold royalty income constitutes the principal source of the Trust&#146;s revenue.&#160; Royalty rates are determined in accordance with the terms of Mesabi Trust&#146;s leases and assignments of leases.&#160; Three types of royalties, as well as royalty bonuses, comprise the Trust&#146;s royalty income:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<U>
	Base overriding royalties
</U>
	.&#160; Base overriding royalties have historically constituted the majority of Mesabi Trust&#146;s royalty income.&#160; Base overriding royalties are determined by both the volume and selling price of iron ore products shipped.&#160; Northshore is obligated to pay Mesabi Trust base overriding royalties in varying amounts, based on the volume of iron ore products shipped.&#160; Base overriding royalties are calculated as a percentage of the gross proceeds of iron ore products produced at Mesabi Trust Lands (and to a limited extent other lands) and shipped from Silver Bay, Minnesota.&#160; The percentage ranges from 2-1/2% of the gross proceeds for the first one million tons of iron ore products so shipped annually to 6% of the gross proceeds for all iron ore products in excess of 4 million tons so shipped annually.&#160; Base overriding royalties are subject to interim and final price adjustments under the Cliffs Pellet Agreements (described on page&nbsp;13 of this Annual Report) and, as described elsewhere in this report, such adjustments may be positive or negative.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<U>
	Royalty bonuses
</U>
	.&#160; The Trust earns royalty bonuses when iron ore products shipped from Silver Bay are sold at prices above a threshold price per ton.&#160; The royalty bonus is based on a percentage of the gross proceeds of product shipped from Silver Bay.&#160; The threshold price is adjusted (but not below $30.00 per ton) on an annual basis for inflation and deflation (the &#147;Adjusted Threshold Price&#148;).&#160; The Adjusted Threshold Price was $52.31 per ton for calendar year 2014 and $53.01 per ton for calendar year 2015, and will be $53.80 per ton for calendar year 2016.&#160; The royalty bonus percentage ranges from 1/2 of 1% of the gross proceeds (on all tonnage shipped for sale at prices between the Adjusted Threshold Price and $2.00 above the Adjusted Threshold Price) to 3% of the gross proceeds (on all tonnage shipped for sale at prices $10.00 or more above the Adjusted Threshold Price).&#160; Royalty bonuses are subject to price adjustments under the Cliffs Pellet Agreements (described on page&nbsp;13 of this Annual Report); such adjustments may be positive or negative.&#160; See the section entitled &#147;Comparison of Financial Results for Fiscal Years ended January&nbsp;31, 2015 and January&nbsp;31, 2014&#148; beginning on page&nbsp;15 of this Annual Report for more information.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<U>
	Fee royalties
</U>
	.&#160; Fee royalties have historically constituted a smaller component of the Trust&#146;s total royalty income.&#160; Fee royalties are payable to the Mesabi Land Trust, a Minnesota land trust, which holds a 20% interest as fee owner in the Peters Lease.&#160; Mesabi Trust holds the entire beneficial interest in the Mesabi Land Trust for which U.S. Bank N.A. acts as the corporate trustee.&#160; Mesabi Trust receives the net income of the Mesabi Land Trust, which is generated from royalties on the amount of crude ore mined after the payment of expenses to U.S. Bank N.A. for its services as the corporate trustee.&#160; Crude ore is the source of iron oxides used to make iron ore pellets and other products.&#160; The fee royalty on crude ore is based on an agreed price per ton, subject to certain indexing.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<U>
	Minimum advance royalties
</U>
	. &#160;Northshore&#146;s obligation to pay base overriding royalties and royalty bonuses with respect to the sale of iron ore products generally accrues upon the shipment of those products from Silver Bay.&#160; However,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	9
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_9_121404_8146">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='9',FILE='C:\JMS\108184\16-4593-1\TASK7891368\4593-1-KU-01.HTM',USER='108184',CD='APR 15 00:46 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage24"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	regardless of whether any shipment has occurred, Northshore is obligated to pay to Mesabi Trust a minimum advance royalty.&#160; Each year, the amount of the minimum advance royalty is adjusted (but not below $500,000 per annum) for inflation and deflation.&#160; The minimum advance royalty was $872,156 for calendar year 2014 and $883,875 for calendar year 2015, and will be $897,008 for calendar year 2016.&#160; Until overriding royalties (and royalty bonuses, if any) for a particular year equal or exceed the minimum advance royalty for the year, Northshore must make quarterly payments of up to 25% of the minimum advance royalty for the year.&#160; Because minimum advance royalties are essentially prepayments of base overriding royalties and royalty bonuses earned each year, any minimum advance royalties paid in a fiscal quarter are recouped by credits against base overriding royalties and royalty bonuses earned in later fiscal quarters during the year.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The current royalty rate schedule became effective on August&nbsp;17, 1989 pursuant to the Amended Assignment Agreements, which the Trust entered into with Cyprus Northshore Mining Corporation (&#147;Cyprus NMC&#148;).&#160; Pursuant to the Amended Assignment Agreements, overriding royalties are determined by both the volume and selling price of iron ore products shipped.&#160; In 1994, Cyprus NMC was sold by its parent corporation to Cliffs and renamed Northshore Mining Company.&#160; Cliffs now operates Northshore as a wholly owned subsidiary.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Under the relevant agreements, Northshore has the right to mine and ship iron ore products from lands other than Mesabi Trust Lands.&#160; Northshore alone determines whether to conduct mining operations on Mesabi Trust Lands and/or such other lands based on its current mining and engineering plan.&#160; The Trustees do not exert any influence over mining operational decisions.&#160; To encourage the use of iron ore products from Mesabi Trust Lands, Mesabi Trust receives royalties on stated percentages of iron ore shipped from Silver Bay, whether or not the iron ore products are from Mesabi Trust Lands.&#160; Mesabi Trust receives royalties at the greater of (i)&nbsp;the aggregate quantity of iron ore products shipped that were mined from Mesabi Trust Lands, and (ii)&nbsp;a portion of the aggregate quantity of all iron ore products shipped from Silver Bay that were mined from any lands, such portion being 90% of the first four million tons shipped from Silver Bay during such year, 85% of the next two million tons shipped during such year, and 25% of all tonnage shipped during such year in excess of six million tons.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Royalty income, which constitutes the principal source of the Trust&#146;s revenue, comprised 99.9% of the Trust&#146;s total revenue in each of the fiscal years ended January&nbsp;31, 2016, January&nbsp;31, 2015 and January&nbsp;31, 2014.&#160; A more complete discussion of royalty rates and the manner in which they are determined is set forth under the headings &#147;Leasehold Royalties&#148; and &#147;Land Trust and Fee Royalties,&#148; beginning on pages&nbsp;24 and 26, respectively, of this Annual Report.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	During the course of its fiscal year some portion of royalties expected to be paid to Mesabi Trust is based in part on estimated prices for iron ore products sold under term contracts between Northshore, Cliffs and their customers (the &#147;Cliffs Pellet Agreements&#148;).&#160; The Cliffs Pellet Agreements use estimated prices which are subject to interim and final pricing adjustments, which can be positive or negative, and which adjustments are dependent in part on multiple price and inflation index factors that are not known until after the end of a contract year. Even though Mesabi Trust is not a party to the Cliffs Pellet Agreements, these adjustments can result in significant variations in royalties payable to Mesabi Trust (and in turn the resulting amount available for distribution to Unitholders by the Trust) from quarter to quarter and on a comparative historical basis, and these variations, which can be positive or negative, cannot be predicted by Mesabi Trust.&#160; In either case, these price adjustments will impact future royalties payable to the Trust that become available for distribution to Unitholders.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As described elsewhere in this Annual Report, the royalty percentage paid to the Trust increases as the aggregate tonnage of iron ore products shipped, attributable to the Trust, in any calendar year increases past each of the first four one-million ton volume thresholds.&#160; Assuming a consistent sales price per ton throughout a calendar year, shipments of iron ore product attributable to the Trust later in the year generate a higher royalty to the Trust, as total shipments for the year exceed increasing levels of royalty percentages and pass each of the first four one-million ton volume thresholds.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As also described elsewhere in this Annual Report, the Trust receives a bonus royalty equal to a percentage of the gross proceeds of iron ore products (mined from Mesabi Trust lands) shipped from Silver Bay and sold at prices above the Adjusted Threshold Price.&#160; Although 90.0% all of the iron ore products shipped from Silver Bay during calendar 2015 were sold at prices higher than the Adjusted Threshold Price, the Trustees are unable to project whether Cliffs will continue to be able to sell iron ore products at prices above the applicable Adjusted Threshold Price, entitling the Trust to any future bonus royalty payments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	10
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_10_121531_7091">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1.0PT;">
	&nbsp;

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="36%" VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:36.5%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT 10.1PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.1PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Trust expenses

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	(1)
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	The Trust, as a grantor trust, is exempt from federal and state income taxes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	(2)
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	Based on 13,120,010 Units of Beneficial Interest outstanding during all years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	(3)
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	The Trust declares distributions in January&nbsp;of each year and pays such distributions in February&nbsp;which is in the Trust&#146;s next fiscal year.&#160; Because of this, distributions declared generally do not equal the amount of cash distributed in the same fiscal year. During the Trust&#146;s fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016, the Trustees distributed $0.68 per Unit (including $0.64 per Unit declared in fiscal 2015 but distributed in fiscal 2016 (February&nbsp;2015)) and in fiscal 2016 declared a distribution of $0.05 per Unit payable in February&nbsp;2016, the next fiscal year.&#160; During the Trust&#146;s fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2015, the Trustees distributed $1.77 per Unit (including $0.57 per Unit declared in fiscal 2014 but distributed in fiscal 2015 (February&nbsp;2014)) and in fiscal 2015 declared a distribution of $0.64 per Unit payable in February&nbsp;2015, the next fiscal year.&#160; During the Trust&#146;s fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2014, the Trustees distributed $1.54 per Unit (including $0.49 per Unit declared in fiscal 2013 but distributed in fiscal 2014 (February&nbsp;2013)) and in fiscal 2014 declared a distribution of $0.57 per Unit payable in February&nbsp;2014, the next fiscal year. During the Trust&#146;s fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2013, the Trustees distributed $2.595 per Unit (including $0.76 per Unit declared in fiscal 2012 but distributed in fiscal 2013 (February&nbsp;2012)) and in fiscal 2013 declared a distribution of $0.49 per Unit payable in February&nbsp;2013, the next fiscal year. During the Trust&#146;s fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2012, the Trustees distributed $2.42 per Unit (including $0.65 per Unit declared in fiscal 2011 but distributed in fiscal 2012 (February&nbsp;2011)) and in fiscal 2012 declared a distribution of $0.76 per Unit payable in February&nbsp;2012, the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	TRUSTEES&#146; DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Results of Operations
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Comparison of Iron Ore Pellet Production and Shipments for the Fiscal Years Ended January&nbsp;31, 2016, January&nbsp;31, 2015 and January&nbsp;31, 2014
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.6IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	During fiscal 2016, production attributed to Trust lands totaled approximately 3.5 million tons, a decrease of 28.9% as compared to production for fiscal year 2015 and a decrease of 10.5% as compared to production for fiscal 2014.&#160; Shipments to Northshore&#146;s customers attributed to the Trust totaled approximately 3.5 million tons during fiscal 2016.&#160; This represents a decrease of 24.1% as compared to shipments for fiscal year 2015 and a decrease of 9.6% as compared to shipments for fiscal year 2014.&#160; The table below, which is based on information provided to the Trust by Northshore, shows the total production and total shipments of iron ore pellets from Mesabi Trust lands during the prior three fiscal years.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

	Production of iron ore pellets for the fourth quarter of fiscal 2016 decreased 77.1% as compared to production of iron ore pellets for the fourth quarter of fiscal 2015 due primarily to a decrease in orders from Northshore&#146;s customers as they adjusted production based on anticipated demand from their customers. Shipments of iron ore pellets by Northshore during the fourth quarter of fiscal 2016

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.6IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As is the case with the volume of shipments from Silver Bay, Minnesota, the Trustees cannot predict what percentage of production or shipments will be attributable to iron ore mined from Mesabi Trust lands in fiscal 2016.&#160; However, pursuant to the Amendment, Mesabi Trust will be credited with at least 90% of the first four million tons of iron ore pellets shipped from Silver Bay, Minnesota in each calendar year, at least 85% of the next two million tons of pellets shipped from Silver Bay, Minnesota in each calendar year, and at least 25% of all tons of pellets shipped from Silver Bay, Minnesota in each calendar year in excess of six million tons.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .4IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.4IN;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Comparison of Financial Results for Fiscal Years ended January&nbsp;31, 2016 and January&nbsp;31, 2015
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.6IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Royalty Income
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.6IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As shown in the table below, in fiscal 2016 base royalties decreased by 50.1%, bonus royalties decreased by 82.1% and fee royalties decreased by 38.0%, each as compared to fiscal 2015.&#160; Accordingly, the Trust&#146;s total royalty income decreased by 62.7% in fiscal 2016 as compared to fiscal 2015.&#160; The decrease in royalties received by the Trust is primarily the result of a decrease in production and shipments in fiscal 2016, as compared to fiscal 2015.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:39.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The royalty amounts set forth in the table above include pricing adjustments made to royalty payments previously received by the Trust based on shipments from Silver Bay, Minnesota during prior calendar years.&#160; Depending on the year, the volume of shipments, and the interim and final price paid to the Trust for shipments from Silver Bay, Minnesota, the price adjustment provisions of the Cliffs Pellet Agreements may increase or decrease, in some cases materially, the royalties paid to the Trust.&#160; Because the Trust is not a party to the Cliffs Pellet Agreements, the Trustees are unable to predict the extent of any pricing adjustments that may occur under the Cliffs Pellet Agreements or whether the adjustments will increase or decrease royalties payable to the Trust. With the current volatility in demand and prices for iron ore and steel products, the price adjustment provisions in the Cliffs Pellet Agreements may have a significant impact on future royalties payable to the Trust and the adjustments, depending on whether they are positive or negative, may increase or decrease the distributions payable to Unitholders.
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As discussed in the paragraph above, the Trust&#146;s total royalty income and net income for fiscal 2016 decreased by 62.7% and 65.4%, respectively, due to a decrease in the amount of iron ore tons shipped during fiscal 2016, both as compared to fiscal 2015. The decrease in the Trust&#146;s net income resulted in a 95.1% decrease in total distributions declared to Unitholders in fiscal 2016, as compared to fiscal year 2015.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The 457.9%
</FONT>
	increase in the Unallocated Reserve for the fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016 as compared the fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2015, resulted from the Trustees&#146; decision to add to the Trust&#146;s cash reserve for unexpected obligations, which is primarily attributable to the idling of iron ore pellet production at Northshore Mining Company in Silver Bay, Minnesota, as announced on November&nbsp;17, 2015 and the Trustees&#146; determination that it is prudent, at this time, to maintain an appropriate level of unallocated reserve for the Trust in order to make adequate provision for current and future expenses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Accrued Income Receivable
</FONT>
</I>
	.&#160; The $419,761, or 75.2%, increase in the accrued income receivable portion of the Unallocated Reserve is the result of pricing adjustments recognized in the last month of the fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016, as compared to the fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As described elsewhere in this Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K, pricing estimates are adjusted on a quarterly basis as updated pricing information is received from Northshore.&#160; It is possible that future negative price adjustments could offset, or even eliminate, royalties or royalty income that would otherwise be payable to the Trust in any particular quarter, or at year end, thereby potentially reducing cash available for distribution to the Trust&#146;s Unitholders in future quarters.&#160; See discussion under the heading &#147;Risk Factors&#148; beginning on page&nbsp;3 of this Annual Report.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Unallocated Cash and U.S. Government Securities.
</FONT>
</I>
	&#160; The Trust&#146;s unallocated cash and U.S. Government Securities for unexpected obligations increased by 674.4% to $8,127,881 as of January&nbsp;31, 2016 from $1,087,469 as of January&nbsp;31, 2015.&#160; The $7,040,412 increase in the Trust&#146;s cash reserve resulted from the Trustees&#146; decision to add to the Trust&#146;s cash reserve for unexpected obligations, which is primarily attributable to the idling of iron ore pellet production at Northshore Mining Company in Silver Bay,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">

	Minnesota, as announced on November&nbsp;17, 2015 and the Trustees&#146; determination that it is prudent, at this time, to maintain an appropriate level of unallocated reserve for the Trust in order to make adequate provision for current and future expenses.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .4IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.4IN;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Comparison of Financial Results for Fiscal Years ended January&nbsp;31, 2015 and January&nbsp;31, 2014
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.6IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Royalty Income
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.6IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As shown in the table below, in fiscal 2015 base royalties increased by 20.6%, bonus royalties increased by 14.8% and fee royalties increased by 23.4%, each as compared to fiscal 2014.&#160; Accordingly, the Trust&#146;s total royalty income increased by 18.3% in fiscal 2015 as compared to fiscal 2014.&#160; The increase in royalties received by the Trust is primarily the result of an increase in production and shipments in fiscal 2015, as compared to fiscal 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:39.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The royalty amounts set forth in the table above include pricing adjustments made to royalty payments previously received by the Trust based on shipments from Silver Bay, Minnesota during prior calendar years.&#160; Depending on the year, the volume of shipments, and the interim and final price paid to the Trust for shipments from Silver Bay, Minnesota, the price adjustment provisions of the Cliffs Pellet Agreements may increase or decrease, in some cases materially, the royalties paid to the Trust.&#160; Because the Trust is not a party to the Cliffs Pellet Agreements, the Trustees are unable to predict the extent of any pricing adjustments that may occur under the Cliffs Pellet Agreements or whether the adjustments will increase or decrease royalties payable to the Trust. With the current volatility in demand and prices for iron ore and steel products, the price adjustment provisions in the Cliffs Pellet Agreements may have a significant impact on future royalties payable to the Trust and the adjustments, depending on whether they are positive or negative, may increase or decrease the distributions payable to Unitholders.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Total Revenues, Expenses, Net Income and Distributions
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.6IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As set forth in the table below, net income for fiscal 2015 increased by 17.6%, as compared to fiscal 2014, primarily due to an increase in total shipments of iron ore pellets. Total expenses for fiscal 2015 increased by 32.7% as compared to fiscal 2014. A more detailed summary of the Trust&#146;s expenses, including legal and accounting expenses, is set forth under the heading &#147;Trust Expenses&#148; on page&nbsp;33 of this Annual Report.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As discussed in the paragraph above, the Trust&#146;s total royalty income and net income for fiscal 2015 increased by 18.3% and 17.6%, respectively, due to an increase in the amount of iron ore tons shipped during fiscal 2015, both as compared to fiscal 2014. The increase in the Trust&#146;s net income resulted in a 13.6% increase in total distributions declared to Unitholders in fiscal 2015, as compared to fiscal year 2014.
</FONT>
