<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The 63.7%
</FONT>
	increase in the Unallocated Reserve for the fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2015 as compared the fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2014, is primarily the result of an increase in the accrued income receivable caused by an increase in the amount of iron ore pellets shipped in January&nbsp;2015 as compared to January&nbsp;2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Accrued Income Receivable
</FONT>
</I>
	.&#160; The $495,132, or 782.8%, increase in the accrued income receivable portion of the Unallocated Reserve is the result of an increase in the amount of iron ore pellets shipped in the last month of the fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2015, as compared to the fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As described elsewhere in this Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K, pricing estimates are adjusted on a quarterly basis as updated pricing information is received from Northshore.&#160; It is possible that future negative price adjustments could offset, or even eliminate, royalties or royalty income that would otherwise be payable to the Trust in any particular quarter, or at year end, thereby potentially reducing cash available for distribution to the Trust&#146;s Unitholders in future quarters.&#160; See discussion under the heading &#147;Risk Factors&#148; beginning on page&nbsp;3 of this Annual Report.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Unallocated Cash and U.S. Government Securities.
</FONT>
</I>
	&#160; The Trust&#146;s unallocated cash and U.S. Government Securities for unexpected obligations increased by 13.6% to $1,087,469 as of January&nbsp;31, 2015 from $957,185 as of January&nbsp;31, 2014.&#160; The $130,284 increase in the Trust&#146;s cash reserve resulted from the Trustees&#146; decision to add to the Trust&#146;s cash reserve for unexpected obligations. The Trust&#146;s current cash reserve as of January&nbsp;31, 2015 is slightly above the range contemplated by the policy set by the Trustees.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Liquidity and Capital Resources
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Trust&#146;s activities are limited to the collection of royalty income, payment of expenses and liabilities, distribution of net income to the Trust&#146;s Unitholders and protection and conservation of Trust assets.&#160; Distributions of net income to the Trust&#146;s Unitholders are based on the amount of total royalty income after providing for the payment of expenses and, to the extent deemed prudent by the Trustees, reserving funds in the Unallocated Reserve to provide for potential fixed or contingent future liabilities, including potential future liabilities that cannot be accurately quantified.&#160; See the discussion of the Trustees&#146; management of liquidity set forth under the heading &#147;Unallocated Reserve&#148; beginning on page&nbsp;34 of this Annual Report.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.6IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Trust&#146;s primary short-term liquidity needs are related to the Trust&#146;s distributions to its Unitholders following the Trust&#146;s receipt of royalty payments from Northshore each calendar quarter.&#160; After the Trust receives the royalty payments, the Trust&#146;s current assets are invested in U.S. government securities, either through direct purchases of U.S. government securities or through investments in a money market fund that invests its assets in U.S. Treasury securities and securities guaranteed by the U.S. government, its agencies or instrumentalities, or the FDIC.&#160; Due to the short-term duration and investment grade nature of these investments, the Trustees believe that the Trust&#146;s current assets are adequate to meet the Trust&#146;s currently foreseeable liquidity needs. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, the Trust held $2,587,165 in cash and cash equivalents of which $2,499,706 was invested in a money market fund that exclusively invests in obligations of the U.S. Treasury.&#160; In February&nbsp;2016, the Trust distributed $656,001 to Unitholders of record on January&nbsp;30, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Off-Balance Sheet Arrangements
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Trust has no off-balance sheet arrangements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Contractual Obligations
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Trust has no payment obligations under any long-term borrowings, capital lease, operating lease, or purchase agreement.
</FONT>
</P>

<A NAME="eolPage30"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Critical Accounting Estimates
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	This &#147;Trustees&#146; Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations&#148; is based upon the Trust&#146;s financial statements, which have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States.&#160; The preparation of these financial statements requires the Trustees to make estimates and judgments that affect the reported amounts of assets, liabilities, revenues and expenses, and related disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities.&#160; These estimates form the basis for making judgments about the carrying value of assets and liabilities that are not readily apparent from other sources.&#160; The Trustees base their estimates and judgments on historical experience and on various other assumptions that the Trustees believe are reasonable under the circumstances.&#160; However, because future events and their effects cannot be determined with certainty, actual results could differ from our assumptions and estimates, and such differences could be material.&#160; Critical accounting policies are those that have meaningful impact on the reporting of the Trust&#146;s financial condition and results of operations, and that require significant judgment and estimates.&#160; For a complete description of the Trust&#146;s significant accounting policies, please see Note 2 to the financial statements on pages&nbsp;F-9 through F-12.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Revenue Recognition
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Royalty income under the Amended Assignment Agreements with Northshore is recognized as it is earned. Under the Amended Assignment Agreements, royalties are earned upon shipment from Silver Bay, Minnesota, regardless of whether the actual sales proceeds for any shipment are received by Northshore.&#160; The amount of base overriding royalties and royalty bonuses payable to the Trust are determined based on the volume of iron ore tonnage shipped from Silver Bay, Minnesota during each calendar quarter and the proceeds to Cliffs resulting from shipments by Cliffs to its customers in accordance with the iron ore pellet sales agreements between Cliffs and its customers.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Trust&#146;s royalty income includes accrued income receivable.&#160; Accrued income receivable represents royalty income earned but not yet received by the Trust.&#160;&#160; Accrued income receivable is calculated using estimated prices and includes (i)&nbsp;shipments during the last month of Mesabi Trust&#146;s fiscal year, if any, and (ii)&nbsp;net positive adjustments (which may include the sum of positive and negative price adjustments) calculated using the pricing adjustment mechanisms in the iron ore pellet sales agreements between Cliffs and its customers that determine the final sales price of the shipments from Silver Bay, Minnesota.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Adjustments to royalty income may result from changes in final reconciliations of tonnage shipped by Northshore with the final amounts received from Cliffs&#146; customers.&#160; Adjustments may also result from revisions to estimated prices previously used to record revenue for tonnage shipped.&#160; Pricing decreases may give rise to negative price adjustments which may be applied against future royalty income recognized by the Trust and changes in iron ore pellet prices may have a significant impact on the revenue recognized by the Trust.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	During the fourth quarter of fiscal 2015, negative price adjustments were recorded by Mesabi Trust and offset against accrued income receivable due to price adjustment mechanisms in the agreements between Cliffs and its customers that determine the final sales price of the shipments from Northshore with respect to certain shipments during calendar year 2014. During the fiscal year ended January&nbsp;31, 2016, positive price adjustments were recorded by Mesabi Trust and added to accrued income receivable due to price adjustment mechanisms in the agreements between Cliffs and its customers that determine the final sales price of the shipments from Northshore with respect to shipments during calendar year 2015.&#160; As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, the Trust recognized revenue related to approximately 880,432 tons of iron ore that were shipped by Northshore as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, but for which Cliffs has indicated that final pricing was not yet known.&#160; Pricing related to these shipments is expected to be finalized in the first quarter of calendar 2017.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Recent Developments
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Northshore Idling and Restart Announcement
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
	. As reported previously, iron ore pellet production at Northshore has been temporarily idled since December&nbsp;1, 2015. On March&nbsp;14, 2016, Cliffs announced that it will be restarting iron ore pellet production at its Northshore mining operation in Minnesota by May&nbsp;15, 2016. Cliffs stated that it is taking such action based on its domestic customers&#146; demand for iron ore pellets and consistent with its previously announced production plans for the year. The Trustees are unable to predict what impact, if any, the idled operations will have on production and shipments from Northshore or future royalties payable to the Trust.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Shipping Estimates
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
	.&#160; Neither Cliffs nor Northshore has provided the Trust with an estimate of production or shipments of iron ore pellets or concentrate for the remainder of calendar year 2016.&#160; Northshore has not advised the Trustees as to the percentage of iron ore products from Mesabi Trust Lands it anticipates shipping in calendar year 2016. See also the description of the uncertainty of market conditions in the iron ore and steel industry under the heading &#147;Risk Factors&#148; above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	16
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_16_123241_7748">
</A>
</P>

<A NAME="eolPage31"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Mercury TMDL and Minnesota Taconite Mercury Reduction Strategy
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
	. TMDL (a regulatory term describing a value of the maximum amount of a pollutant that a body of water can receive while still meeting water quality standards under the Clean Water Act) regulations are contained in the Clean Water Act and as a part of Minnesota&#146;s Mercury TMDL Implementation Plan, in cooperation with the MPCA, the taconite industry developed a Taconite Mercury Reduction Strategy and signed a voluntary agreement to effectuate its terms. The strategy includes a 75 percent target reduction of mercury air emissions from Minnesota pellet plants collectively by 2025. For Cliffs, the requirements in the voluntary agreement do not apply to Northshore. Late in 2013, however, Minnesota published a draft mercury control rule&nbsp;that would require annual mercury emissions reporting and could require installation of mercury emission control equipment on all Cliffs&#146; Minnesota facilities including those of Northshore. On September&nbsp;22, 2014, Minnesota promulgated the Mercury Air Emissions Reporting and Reduction Rule&nbsp;mandating mercury air emissions reporting and reduction. The adopted rule&nbsp;expanded applicability to all of Cliffs&#146; Minnesota operations and requires submitting a mercury reduction plan in 2018 to reduce mercury emissions from all of Cliffs&#146; Minnesota taconite furnaces by 72 percent by January&nbsp;2025 and 70 percent reduction from Northshore&#146;s industrial boilers by January&nbsp;1, 2018. The adopted rule&nbsp;does not include all four Adaptive Management Criteria for evaluating mercury reduction, which were agreed upon in the October&nbsp;2009 Minnesota&#146;s Mercury TMDL Implementation Plan. According to Cliffs&#146; Form&nbsp;10-K filed February&nbsp;24, 2016, there is currently no proven technology to cost-effectively reduce mercury emissions from taconite furnaces to the target level of 72 percent that would meet all four Adaptive Management Criteria. Cliffs expressed its concerns about the technical and economic feasibility to reduce taconite mercury emissions by 72 percent and are conducting detailed engineering analysis to determine the impact of the regulations on each unique iron ore indurating furnace affected by this rule. The Trustees are unable to predict what impact, if any, the Mercury Air Emissions Reporting and Reduction Rule&nbsp;will have on production and shipments from Northshore or future royalties payable to the Trust.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:39.0PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Cross State Air Pollution Rule
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
	. In its Form&nbsp;10-K filed February&nbsp;24, 2016, Cliffs reported that on July&nbsp;6, 2011, the US Environmental Protection Agency (the &#147;EPA&#148;) promulgated the Cross State Air Pollution Rule&nbsp;(the &#147;CSAPR&#148;), which was intended to be an emissions trading rule&nbsp;for SO2 and NOx. Northshore&#146;s Silver Bay Power Plant would have been subject to this rule. CSAPR was vacated by the D.C. Circuit Court during the third quarter of 2012. Late in 2014, the Supreme Court re-instated CSAPR with an effective date of January&nbsp;1, 2015, reinstating the obligations of this rule&nbsp;for Silver Bay Power. In January, 2016, the 8th Circuit Court of Appeals re-affirmed EPA use of CSAPR is equal to or better than BART. Immediate compliance obligations are being met at this time, with the material obligation being procurement of the first year of emissions allowances by March&nbsp;2016 for the 2015 operating year. Silver Bay Power has installed low NOx burners to reduce emissions that will limit the cost exposure to the emission trading market. The allowance pricing market indicates the annual costs to comply with CSAPR will be less than $0.2 million for 2015 and future allowance prices are anticipated to remain favorable under the existing framework. Cliffs cautioned in its most recent Form&nbsp;10-K that it cannot reasonably estimate the long term impact of CSAPR should EPA reduce the allocations in response to future lower ozone or PM2.5 regulations.&#160; The Trustees are unable to predict what impact, if any, the emission reductions will have on production and shipments from Northshore or future royalties payable to the Trust.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Securities Regulation
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
	.&#160; The Trust is a publicly traded, pass-through royalty trust with its Trust Certificates listed on the New York Stock Exchange (&#147;NYSE&#148;) and is therefore subject to extensive regulation under, among others, the Securities Act of 1933, the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002 (&#147;Sarbanes-Oxley&#148;), each as amended, and the rules&nbsp;and regulations of the NYSE.&#160; Issuers failing to comply with such authorities risk serious consequences, including criminal as well as civil and administrative penalties.&#160; In most instances, these laws, rules&nbsp;and regulations do not specifically address their applicability to a publicly-traded pass-through royalty trust such as Mesabi Trust.&#160; In particular, Sarbanes-Oxley mandated the adoption by the Securities and Exchange Commission and NYSE of certain rules&nbsp;and regulations that are impossible for the Trust to literally satisfy because of its nature as a pass-through trust.&#160; Pursuant to NYSE rules, as a pass-through royalty trust, the Trust is exempt from many of the corporate governance requirements that apply to other publicly traded corporations.&#160; The Trust does not have, nor does the Agreement of Trust provide for, a board of directors, an audit committee, a corporate governance committee, a compensation committee or executive officers.&#160; The Trustees closely monitor the Securities and Exchange Commission&#146;s and NYSE&#146;s rulemaking activities and will comply with their rules&nbsp;and regulations to the extent applicable.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Essar Litigation
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
	. As disclosed in Cliffs&#146; Form&nbsp;10-K filed February&nbsp;24, 2016, the Cleveland-Cliffs Iron Company, Northshore and Cliffs Mining Company (collectively, the &#147;Cliffs Plaintiffs&#148;) filed a complaint against Essar in the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Ohio, Eastern Division, on January&nbsp;12, 2015, asserting that Essar breached the Essar Sale Agreement by, among other things, failing to take delivery of and pay for its nominated ore in 2014, failing to make certain payments under a true up provision, and disclosing confidential information. The complaint also seeks a declaration that Essar is not entitled to receive certain credit payments under the terms of the Essar Sale Agreement. The Cliffs Plaintiffs seek damages in excess of $90 million. Essar filed an Answer and Counterclaim on February&nbsp;11, 2015, seeking damages in excess of $160 million for various alleged breaches of the Essar Sale Agreement, including failure to deliver ore, overcharging for certain deliveries, failure to pay certain credit payments and disclosing confidential information. The parties started the discovery process, with a discovery cutoff date set for October&nbsp;30, 2015, and a trial date set for December&nbsp;7, 2015. The parties agreed to attempt mediation of the claims. Two mediation sessions took place on March&nbsp;7 and April&nbsp;21, 2015. The mediations were unsuccessful. The Cliffs Plaintiffs filed a Motion for Partial Summary Judgment on July&nbsp;31, 2015, which was granted in part on October&nbsp;8, 2015. With respect to the Cliffs Plaintiffs&#146; claim that Essar had breached by
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	17
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_17_120815_1870">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='17',FILE='C:\JMS\107536\16-4593-1\TASK7891402\4593-1-KU-05.HTM',USER='107536',CD='APR 15 00:56 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage32"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	failing to take its 2014 nomination, the Court found that Essar had breached and had failed to take between 500,000 and 700,000 tons of its 2014 nomination. The summary judgment ruling also dismissed Essar&#146;s counterclaim that the Cliffs Plaintiffs had overcharged Essar by improperly measuring moisture levels. With respect to this claim, the Court found that there was &#147;no basis&#148; for Essar&#146;s claim that the Cliffs Plaintiffs had breached the contract. On October&nbsp;5, 2015, the Cliffs Plaintiffs terminated the Pellet Agreement because of Essar&#146;s continual breach of the Pellet Agreement. On October&nbsp;6, 2015, Essar filed motions for temporary restraining order and preliminary injunction. Essar withdrew both motions on October&nbsp;15, 2015, before any order was entered on either motion. On November&nbsp;9, 2015, Essar filed for protection under CCAA in Canada in the Ontario Superior Court of Justice and Chapter 15 bankruptcy protection in the United States in the U.S. District Court for the District of Delaware. As a result of the stay related to Essar&#146;s bankruptcy proceedings, the litigation in U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Ohio was dismissed without prejudice stating that either party could reinstate the case upon application, if necessary, when the bankruptcy proceedings have concluded. Essar moved the CCAA Court to determine that the Cliffs Plaintiffs&#146; termination of the Pellet Agreement was invalid and to reinstate the Pellet Agreement. The Cliffs Plaintiffs have objected based upon inappropriate jurisdiction and other grounds. On January&nbsp;25, 2016, the CCAA Court determined that it has proper jurisdiction and instructed the parties to determine an appropriate procedure to try the facts in front of the CCAA Court. The Cliffs Plaintiffs filed an appeal of the CCAA Court&#146;s decision regarding proper jurisdiction on February&nbsp;8, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Trustees are unable to predict what impact, if any, this litigation will have on production and shipments from Northshore or future royalties payable to the Trust.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Review of Unallocated Reserve.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
	Prior to April&nbsp;2015, the Trustees had determined that the Unallocated Reserve should usually be within the range of $500,000 to $1,000,000. As previously disclosed, in April&nbsp;2015, the Trustees determined that the Unallocated Reserve will no longer necessarily be within such range. Rather, each quarter, as authorized by the Agreement of Trust, the Trustees will evaluate all relevant factors including all costs, expenses, charges, obligations, and present and future liabilities (whether known or contingent) of the Trust in determining a prudent level of Unallocated Reserve in light of the unpredictable nature of the iron ore industry and current economic conditions. As of January&nbsp;31, 2016, the Trust&#146;s unallocated reserve was $8,989,164.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Other Information
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
	.&#160; Mesabi Trust has no employees.&#160; Each year the Trust engages independent consultants to assist the Trustees in monitoring, among other things, the volume and sales prices of iron ore products shipped by Northshore from Silver Bay, Minnesota and in reviewing all records and calculations of the same each quarter.&#160; As noted above, the information regarding volume and sales prices of shipped iron ore products is used to compute the royalties payable to Mesabi Trust by Northshore.&#160; Deutsche Bank Trust Company Americas, the Corporate Trustee, also performs certain administrative functions for Mesabi Trust.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	TO THE HOLDERS OF
<BR>
	CERTIFICATES OF BENEFICIAL INTEREST IN
<BR>
	MESABI TRUST
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	THE TRUST ESTATE
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The principal assets of Mesabi Trust consist of two different interests in certain properties in the Mesabi Iron Range: (i)&nbsp;Mesabi Trust&#146;s interest as assignor in the Amended Assignment of Peters Lease and the Amended Assignment of Cloquet Lease, which together cover properties aggregating approximately 9,750 largely contiguous acres in St. Louis County, Minnesota (the &#147;Peters Lease Lands&#148; and the &#147;Cloquet Lease Lands,&#148; respectively), and (ii)&nbsp;Mesabi Trust&#146;s ownership of the entire beneficial interest in the Mesabi Land Trust, which has a 20% interest as fee owner in the Peters Lease Lands and a 100% fee ownership in certain non-mineral-bearing lands adjacent to the Peters and Cloquet Lease Lands (the &#147;Mesabi Lease Lands,&#148; together with Mesabi Trust Lands, the &#147;Trust Estate&#148;).&#160; The map below shows the approximate location of the Trust Estate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<IMG WIDTH="675" HEIGHT="474" SRC="http://content.edgar-online.com/edgar_conv_img/2016/04/14/0001104659-16-111488_G45931KU05I001.JPG">
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="WINGDINGS" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	o
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	The boxed area indicates the approximate location of Mesabi Trust&#146;s Trust Estate (not drawn to scale), as defined above under the &#147;Trust Estate,&#148; which is a small part of the region known as the Mesabi Iron Range. Mesabi Trust does not own any property interests other than those in the Trust Estate
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Under the Amended Assignment Agreements, Northshore produces iron ore from Mesabi Trust Lands for the manufacture of iron ore products to be sold to various customers of Cliffs.&#160; Mesabi Trust receives royalties on the crude ore extracted from such lands and the pellets produced from such crude ore, and in each case the royalties are based upon the volume of iron ore products shipped and the prices charged to Cliffs&#146; customers.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_19_120926_5335">
</A>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='19',FILE='C:\JMS\107536\16-4593-1\TASK7891402\4593-1-KU-05.HTM',USER='107536',CD='APR 15 00:56 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage34"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	DURATION OF THE TRUST ESTATE
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The largest component of the Trust Estate is the Peters Lease Lands.&#160; The Peters Lease provides that the leasehold estate thereunder will continue until the reserves of iron ore, taconite and other minerals or materials on the land subject to the Peters Lease are exhausted.&#160; The Amended Assignment of Peters Lease terminates when the Peters Lease terminates.&#160; The Cloquet Lease, executed in 1916, provides that the leasehold estate thereunder will continue until the reserves of iron ore, taconite and other minerals or materials on the land subject to the Cloquet Lease are exhausted. The Amended Assignment of Cloquet Lease terminates when the Cloquet Lease terminates.&#160; If Northshore decides to terminate or surrender either the Amended Assignment of Peters Lease or the Amended Assignment of Cloquet Lease, or both of them, it must first give Mesabi Trust at least six months&#146; notice of its intention to do so and, at Mesabi Trust&#146;s request, reassign all of such leasehold interests to Mesabi Trust.&#160; If any such reassignment occurs, Northshore must transfer the leasehold interests to Mesabi Trust free and clear of liens, except public highways.&#160; In return, Mesabi Trust must assume Northshore&#146;s future obligations as lessee under the reassigned leases. Upon termination of the lease under either the Amended Assignment of Peters Lease or the Amended Assignment of Cloquet Lease, or both of them, Northshore is obligated to remove within 90 days all engines, tools, machinery, railroad tracks and structures erected or placed by it, or under its direction, on the lands but may not remove or impair any supports placed in the mines, nor any timber or frameworks necessary to the use and maintenance of the shafts or other approaches to the mine.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Peters Lease Lands and the Cloquet Lease Lands are located at the northeastern end of the Mesabi Iron Range and contain mineral deposits consisting of a highly metamorphosed sedimentary bed of banded magnetite in siliceous gangue, a form of low-grade iron ore known as taconite, approximately three tons of which must be beneficiated to produce one ton of high-grade pellets.&#160; The Mesabi Lease Lands contain substantially no commercial ore deposits and have been used principally in connection with mining the taconite from other parts of the Trust Estate, such as the provision of an area for location of service roads, supporting plants and equipment and dump sites for overburden.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Because the Trust is not involved with the mining operations at Northshore, the Trust relies on the ore reserve estimates reported in Cliffs&#146; Form&nbsp;10-K filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission each year.&#160; In Cliffs&#146; most recent Form&nbsp;10-K, as filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission, which was for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, the following information was provided by Cliffs regarding the estimated ore reserves at Northshore.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

	(In Millions of Long Tons)

<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">

</TD>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:1.08%;">
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</B>

<TD WIDTH="0%" VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#CCEEFF" STYLE="BACKGROUND:#CCEEFF;PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:.98%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="1" WIDTH="25%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;">
</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	(1)&nbsp;Saleable product is a standard pellet containing 60 to 66 percent Fe calculated from both proven and probable mineral reserves.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	(2)&nbsp;Saleable product is reported on a dry basis; shipped products typically contain 1 to 4 percent moisture.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	(3)&nbsp;Process recovery includes all factors for converting crude ore tonnage to saleable product.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	(4)&nbsp;Cutoff grade was 19%.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	According to Cliffs&#146; Form&nbsp;10-K filed February&nbsp;24, 2016, reserve estimates are based on pricing that does not exceed the three-year trailing average of benchmark prices for iron ore adjusted to Cliffs&#146; realized price. The latest reserve estimate for Northshore was completed in 2015. In its Form&nbsp;10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, Cliffs reported that the average international benchmark price of 62 percent Fe CFR China was $96 per dry metric ton for the three-year period 2013 to 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Trustees engaged an independent geological consulting firm, Roscoe Postle Associates,&nbsp;Inc. (&#147;RPA&#148;), to confirm that the process used by Cliffs to estimate the ore reserves in the mine at Northshore is reasonable.&#160; RPA delivered its report to the Trustees in April&nbsp;2013.&#160; In its report to the Trustees, RPA summarized its review and evaluation of Cliffs&#146; ore reserve estimation process which was performed by Cliffs in 2012.&#160; RPA reported to the Trustees that the reserve estimation process used by Cliffs is reasonable and comports with the reporting requirements set forth in Securities Act Industry Guide 7.&#160; Based on the report of RPA, at least 90% of the ore reserves in the mine at Northshore, as reported by Cliffs, is attributable to Mesabi Trust Lands.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	20
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_20_121822_5796">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='20',FILE='C:\JMS\107536\16-4593-1\TASK7891402\4593-1-KU-05.HTM',USER='107536',CD='APR 15 00:56 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage35"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	HISTORY OF THE TRUST&#146;S ACQUISITION OF THE TRUST ESTATE
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Prior to the creation of Mesabi Trust and Mesabi Land Trust on July&nbsp;18, 1961, Mesabi Iron Company (&#147;MIC&#148;), the Trust&#146;s predecessor in interest, owned the interests in the Peters Lease Lands, Cloquet Lease Lands and Mesabi Lease Lands.&#160; MIC obtained its interests as follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<U>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Peters Lease Lands
</FONT>
</U>
	. MIC owned a 20% interest in the fee ownership in the Peters Lease Lands.&#160; Originally, the Peters Lease Lands were owned by East Mesaba Iron Company and Dunka River Iron Company which were wholly owned subsidiaries of Dunka-Mesaba Security Company (&#147;Dunka-Mesaba&#148;).&#160; In August&nbsp;1951, East Mesaba Iron Company and Dunka River Iron Company conveyed the Peters Lease Lands to their parent company, Dunka-Mesaba, which in turn conveyed to each of its stockholders an undivided interest in the Peters Lease Lands in proportion to each stockholder&#146;s ownership in the parent company.&#160; Accordingly, MIC, which had been the owner of 20% of the outstanding capital stock of Dunka-Mesaba, acquired a 20% undivided interest in the Peters Lease Lands and the right to receive a 20% fee royalty under the Peters Lease.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	By an instrument dated October&nbsp;1, 1917, as of April&nbsp;30, 1915, East Mesaba and Dunka River leased their properties to Claude W. Peters.&#160; This instrument, as modified by instruments dated February&nbsp;3, 1921, July&nbsp;17, 1939 and July&nbsp;31, 1951, is known as the &#147;Peters Lease.&#148;&#160; Claude W. Peters acquired the Peters Lease on behalf of MIC and an assignment of the Peters Lease from Claude W. Peters to MIC was recorded in 1919.&#160; In 1939, MIC assigned the Peters Lease to Reserve Mining Company (&#147;Reserve&#148;) in consideration for which Reserve agreed to pay MIC a percentage of its net profits.&#160; Later, these payments were changed to royalty payments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<U>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Cloquet Lease Lands.
</FONT>
</U>
	&#160; MIC held a leasehold interest in the Cloquet Lease Lands pursuant to the Indenture of Lease dated May&nbsp;1, 1916.&#160; In 1939, MIC assigned its interest in the Cloquet Lease as lessee to Reserve.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<U>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Mesabi Lease Lands.
</FONT>
</U>
	&#160; MIC held a fee interest in the Mesabi Lease Lands, subject to earlier grants of mineral rights to other parties.&#160; In 1939, MIC leased its interest in the Mesabi Lease Lands to Reserve (&#147;Mesabi Lease&#148;).&#160; One 40-acre parcel of the Mesabi Lease Lands was forfeited in the 1980s to the State of Minnesota and subsequently sold to the United States government, excluding the mineral rights granted to other parties. Further, another 40-acre parcel of the Mesabi Lease Lands, for which the Trust owns only surface rights, is currently being explored for non-ferrous deposits by the holder of the mineral rights to the parcel.&#160; The Trustees do not believe that either parcel was ever involved in, or otherwise material to, Northshore&#146;s mining operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<U>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Acquisition of Interests from MIC.
</FONT>
</U>
	&#160; MIC had not engaged in actual mining operations since 1939, with all of its ownership of land in fee having been leased out and its leaseholds in land assigned to Reserve in exchange for royalty payments.&#160; Because MIC&#146;s activities in connection with the administration of its assets were limited to the collection of income, the payment of expenses and liabilities, the distribution of the net income and the protection and conservation of the assets held, in July&nbsp;1961 its board of directors proposed, and its stockholders subsequently approved, to adopt a plan of complete liquidation as a result of which MIC&#146;s assets were transferred to and administered by two trust entities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	To comply with the law of the State of Minnesota, which requires that a trust holding real property located in that state must be administered under Minnesota law, the Mesabi Land Trust was created under Minnesota law on July&nbsp;18, 1961 pursuant to an Agreement of Trust of even date.&#160; MIC transferred to the Mesabi Land Trust its 20% interest as fee owner in the Peters Lease Lands and its interest as 100% fee owner in the Mesabi Lease Lands and as lessor of the Mesabi Lease (subject to the reservation of mineral rights described above).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Also pursuant to an Agreement of Trust, the Mesabi Trust was created under New York law on July&nbsp;18, 1961.&#160; MIC transferred to the Mesabi Trust instruments assigning the Amended Assignment of Peters Lease and the Amended Assignment of Cloquet Lease (covering its interest as assignor of the entire leasehold interest in the Peters Lease Lands and the Cloquet Lease Lands), together with cash, marketable securities and other assets.&#160; The Mesabi Trust also received all of the beneficial interest in the Mesabi Land Trust.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Reserve, the original lessee, operated the mine until it closed on July&nbsp;31, 1986.&#160; Cyprus Minerals Company (&#147;Cyprus&#148;) purchased substantially all of Reserve&#146;s assets on August&nbsp;17, 1989 and resumed operations as Cyprus NMC.&#160; On September&nbsp;30, 1994, Cliffs purchased all of Cyprus NMC&#146;s capital stock from Cyprus.&#160; Cliffs renamed the operation Northshore Mining Corporation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Since the creation of Mesabi Land Trust and Mesabi Trust, although the mining operators have changed and the Peters Lease, the Cloquet Lease and the Mesabi Lease have been further amended and assigned, the Trust Estate has not changed beyond the forfeiture of one parcel of the Mesabi Lease Lands described above.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	21
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_21_121851_2897">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>

<A NAME="eolPage36"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The diagram below illustrates the relationships of the various parties that own the lands and have interests in the lands the Trust has interests in:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<IMG WIDTH="562" HEIGHT="343" SRC="http://content.edgar-online.com/edgar_conv_img/2016/04/14/0001104659-16-111488_G45931KU07I001.JPG">
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	DESCRIPTION OF THE MINERAL PROPERTIES AND NORTHSHORE&#146;S MINING OPERATIONS
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<U>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Mine and Rock Formation
</FONT>
</U>
	.&#160; The Trust Estate, including the ore mine, are located in northeastern Minnesota, approximately two miles south of Babbitt, Minnesota.&#160; The ore mine on the Trust Estate is called the Peter Mitchell Mine, an open pit mine consisting of a 10-mile long segment of a host rock called the Biwabik Iron Formation, which is a very hard cherty rock containing magnetite as the ore mineral.&#160; The Biwabik Iron Formation extends west and southwest for over 100 miles and constitutes the Mesabi Iron Range.&#160; Recoverable iron grades range from 21% magnetic iron in the west end of the mine open pit to 26% magnetic iron in the central portion and east end.&#160; The ore body dips south under the hanging wall called the Virginia Formation.&#160; To date, the Mesabi Trust properties have been explored for their iron ore potential.&#160; To the knowledge of the Mesabi Trustees, no other minerals have been explored on the Trust Estate.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<U>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Mining Properties
</FONT>
</U>
	.&#160; As disclosed elsewhere in this Annual Report, Northshore, a wholly owned subsidiary of Cliffs, currently conducts the mining operation upon the Trust Estate.&#160; The main entrance to the Northshore mine is accessed by means of a gravel road and is located off County Road 70.&#160; Northshore&#146;s processing facilities are located in Silver Bay, Minnesota, near Lake Superior, on U.S. Highway 61.&#160; Each year, the Trustees visit the Northshore mine in Babbitt, Minnesota and the processing plant in Silver Bay, Minnesota.&#160; During such visits, the Trustees inspect the condition of the mining properties as well as mining equipment and facilities.&#160; Based on information provided to the Trustees during the most recent inspection trip in the third fiscal quarter of 2015, the mining properties and facilities at Northshore were in good operating condition.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<U>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Northshore&#146;s Operations
</FONT>
</U>
	.&#160; Because Mesabi Trust is not involved in Northshore&#146;s mining operations, the Trustees do not have detailed firsthand information relating to such operations or the equipment and facilities used by Northshore.&#160; Therefore, the Trustees rely on information provided by Northshore personnel, disclosures by Cliffs in its periodic and current reports filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission and, to some extent, information provided in other reports published by independent organizations, such as Skillings Mining Review, in providing the information relating to Northshore&#146;s mining operations, equipment and facilities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<B>
	Mining and Railroad
</B>
	. Drilling at the Northshore mine is conducted with two P&amp;H 120, one P&amp;H 320XPC, one BE59R, and 1 CAT MD6750 rotary units with 16-inch diameter holes on 25-30 foot spacing and 12 1/4 inch diameter holes on 22 to 25-foot spacing.&#160; The drilling is followed with blasts using a gassed sensitized emulsion which breaks an average of 700,000 to 1,200,000 tons of crude taconite.&#160; After blasts, taconite is then removed by a loading fleet consisting of four P&amp;H 2800 XPC electric rope shovels with 35 to 41-cubic yard buckets and one Letourneau L1850 loader with a 28 cubic yard bucket.&#160; A haulage fleet of three 250-ton Terex Model 4400AC, three 250-ton Komatsu Model 830E, and three 200-ton Komatsu 730E
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	22
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_22_123528_962">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='22',FILE='C:\JMS\109424\16-4593-1\TASK7891371\4593-1-KU-07.HTM',USER='109424',CD='APR 15 00:46 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage37"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_1_122032_3020">
</A>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	production trucks carry crude taconite to the primary and secondary crushers located about two miles away.&#160; At the crushers, taconite is emptied from the end-dump trucks into a 60 inch primary gyratory unit and four 30-inch by 70-inch secondary crushers for reduction to a nominal 4 inch size coarse ore.&#160; The coarse ore is then fed into 90-ton capacity ore cars for transportation to Silver Bay via a 47-mile-long, single track railroad owned by Northshore.&#160; Each train is pulled by three diesel electric locomotives.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<B>
	Concentrating and Pelletizing Process
</B>
	.&#160; Upon arrival at the pelletizing facility in Silver Bay, the coarse taconite ore first passes through a fine crushing stage where it is reduced in size to approximately 0-3/4.&#148; Non-magnetic material is rejected through a dry cobber magnetic separation stage and then rail-hauled seven miles to the Mile Post 7 disposal site. Magnetic material is fed into one of the seventeen active grinding lines.&#160; Each line includes one 10-1/2-foot by 18-foot rod mill and two 10-1/2-foot by 18-foot (16-foot in west plant) ball mills.&#160; The final grinding of the crude taconite is reduced to 90% minus 325 mesh.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	During the concentrating process, ore concentrate is separated by a two-stage magnetic separation, which removes low grade tailings from the ore concentrate.&#160; The tailings are pumped uphill to the Mile Post 7 disposal site.&#160; The concentrate is then fed into hydro-separators followed by a final flotation upgrading accomplished with two 500 cubic foot flotation cells per grinding line.&#160; Next, the concentrate proceeds to a central filtering facility of nine (9)-foot diameter vacuum filters, through which the moisture content in the concentrate is reduced and the final concentrate becomes ready for pelletizing.&#160; The pelletizing process first feeds the ore concentrate, to which bentonite and starch has been added as a binder, into a balling drum 31 feet long and 9 feet in diameter.&#160; The revolving action of the drum causes the concentrate to build up into green balls.&#160; Next, the green balls with a target size of plus 0-1/4&#148; and minus 0-1/2&#148; in diameter are conveyed to one of four moving grates and enter into an accompanying high temperature furnace where they are heated to over 2,400&#176;F and are hardened into the final pellet product.&#160; From the four furnaces the pellets are conveyed to a dockside storage area with a 5-million ton storage capacity.&#160; Northshore&#146;s sheltered harbor at Silver Bay can handle lake-going vessels with capacities up to 55,000 tons.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<B>
	Capital Expenditures
</B>
	.&#160; During calendar year 2015, Northshore continued to modernize and improve the operations at the Peter Mitchell Mine in Babbitt and Northshore&#146;s pelletizing facility in Silver Bay, Minnesota.&#160; Toward that end, Cliffs implemented the following capital expenditures:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT 1.0IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	Installed a Low NOX Burner in Unit #1 at the power plant.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT 1.0IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	Continued investments in projects for safety (arc flash mitigation in the HVAC System).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.3IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;
</FONT>
	&#160;&#160;&#160;
<B>
	N
</B>
<B>
	orthshore Mine Safety and Health Administration Safety Data
</B>
	.&#160; The operation of the Northshore mine is subject to regulation by MSHA under the FMSH Act. In its Form&nbsp;10-K filed February&nbsp;24, 2016, Cliffs reported that MSHA inspects its mines on a regular basis and issues various citations and orders when it believes a violation has occurred under the FMSH Act.&#160; In its Form&nbsp;10-K, Cliffs provided information regarding certain mining safety and health citations which MSHA has issued with respect to Northshore&#146;s mining operations. In evaluating this information, consideration should be given to factors such as: (i)&nbsp;the number of citations and orders will vary depending on the size of the mine, (ii)&nbsp;the number of citations issued will vary from inspector to inspector, and (iii)&nbsp;citations and orders can be contested and appealed, and in that process, are often reduced in severity and amount, and are sometimes dismissed.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Under the recently enacted Dodd-Frank Act, each operator of a coal or other mine is required to include certain mine safety results within its periodic reports filed with the SEC. As required by the reporting requirements included in &#167;1503(a)&nbsp;of the Dodd-Frank Act, in its Form&nbsp;10-K, Cliffs presented the following items regarding certain mining safety and health matters for the Northshore Mine.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT 46.1PT;TEXT-INDENT:-.3IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	(A)
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8.5PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	The total number of violations of mandatory health or safety standards that could significantly and substantially contribute to the cause and effect of a coal or other mine safety or health hazard under section 104 of the FMSH Act (30 U.S.C. 814) for which the operator received a citation from MSHA;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT 46.1PT;TEXT-INDENT:-.3IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	(B)
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8.5PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	The total number of orders issued under section 104(b)&nbsp;of the FMSH Act (30 U.S.C. 814(b));
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT 46.1PT;TEXT-INDENT:-.3IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	(C)
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8.5PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	The total number of citations and orders for unwarrantable failure of the mine operator to comply with mandatory health or safety standards under section 104(d)&nbsp;of the FMSH Act (30 U.S.C. 814(d));
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT 46.1PT;TEXT-INDENT:-.3IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	(D)
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8.5PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	The total number of imminent danger orders issued under section 107(a)&nbsp;of the FMSH Act (30 U.S.C. 817(a));
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;

<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.5IN;">
<HR SIZE="1" WIDTH="25%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;">
</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .25IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8.0PT;">
	(1)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amounts included under the heading &#147;Total Dollar Value of MSHA Proposed Assessments&#148; are the total dollar amounts for proposed assessments received from MSHA on or before December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .3IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.3IN;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8.0PT;">
	(
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8.0PT;">
	2
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8.0PT;">
	)&nbsp;&nbsp;This number consists of 15 pending legal actions related to contests of proposed penalties referenced in Subpart C of FMSH Act&#146;s procedural rules.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	LEASEHOLD ROYALTIES
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Northshore is obligated to pay to Mesabi Trust base overriding royalties and royalty bonuses on all pellets (and other iron ore products) produced from the Peters Lease Lands and the Cloquet Lease Lands (&#147;Mesabi Ore&#148;) and shipped from Silver Bay in each calendar year.&#160; The royalties are based on prices per unit of product, volumes of product shipped and where on the escalating scale of royalties&#151;2-1/2% on the first million long tons to 6% on shipments above four million long tons per calendar year&#151;each shipment falls.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Base overriding royalties
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
	.&#160; Base overriding royalties are calculated on the basis of an escalating scale of percentages of gross sales proceeds of iron ore shipped.&#160; The applicable percentage is determined by reference to the tonnage of pellets (and other iron ore products) previously shipped in the then current calendar year, as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:36.4PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Royalty bonuses.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
	&#160; Royalty bonuses are payable on all iron ore products produced from Mesabi Ore shipped from Silver Bay during a calendar quarter and sold at prices above the Adjusted Threshold Price.&#160; The Adjusted Threshold Price was $52.31 for calendar year 2014 and $53.01 for calendar year 2015, and will be $53.80 for calendar year 2016.&#160; The Adjusted Threshold Price is subject to adjustment (but not below $30 per ton) for inflation and deflation and is determined each year on the basis of the change in
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	24
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_24_123542_8146">
</A>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	the Gross Domestic Product Implicit Price Deflator, a broad-based index of inflation and deflation published quarterly by the U.S. Department of Commerce.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The amount of royalty bonuses payable for any calendar quarter is calculated on the basis of an escalating scale of percentages of the gross sales proceeds to Northshore of pellets produced from Mesabi Ore that are sold at prices above the Adjusted Threshold Price.&#160; The applicable percentage is determined by reference to the amount by which the sales prices for a particular quantity of pellets exceeds the Adjusted Threshold Price, as follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Leasehold royalty example.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
	&#160;&#160;To illustrate the calculation of base overriding royalties and royalty bonuses, assume that no shipments of iron ore products were made during the first calendar quarter of 2016, and further assume that pellets were shipped from Silver Bay in the second and third calendar quarters of 2016 in the following tonnage quantities and rendering the following gross proceeds:
</P>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.5IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The above figures are provided only to illustrate the method for calculating base overriding royalties and royalty bonuses and do not indicate the amount of base overriding royalties or royalty bonuses the Trustees expect Mesabi Trust to earn in calendar 2016 or any other calendar or fiscal year.&#160; Accordingly, the foregoing example illustrating the calculation of base overriding royalties and royalty bonuses should not be considered a prediction of the amount of base overriding royalties or royalty bonuses Mesabi Trust will receive.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	25
<A NAME="A16-4593_1EX13_HTM_PB_25_124424_7091">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
